    <title>functionally-reducing-anti-css</title>
    <link href="https://bloodyaugust.github.io/frontend-feed/2019/05/31/functionally-reducing-anti-css/"/>
    <id>https://bloodyaugust.github.io/frontend-feed/2019/05/31/functionally-reducing-anti-css/</id>
    <published>2019-05-31T22:21:18.000Z</published>
    <updated>2019-05-31T23:07:58.525Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<ul><li><p><a href="https://nystudio107.com/blog/the-css-background-image-property-as-an-anti-pattern" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CSS Background Image Anti-Pattern</a> - For a long time, this attribute was used for dynamically sizing images, but now you should use <code>picture</code>. - <a href="https://frontendfoc.us/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">From</a></p></li><li><p><a href="http://bradfrost.com/blog/post/reducing-motion-with-the-picture-element/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Reducing Picture Motion</a> - Use the <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> media query to support still images for accessibility purposes. - <a href="https://frontendfoc.us/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">From</a></p></li><li><p><a href="https://jrsinclair.com/articles/2019/five-ways-to-average-with-js-reduce/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">More JS Reduce Fun</a> - A follow-on from last week, this is another great article discussing how to use <code>reduce</code> in JS land. - <a href="https://javascriptweekly.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">From</a></p></li><li><p><a href="https://github.com/scrumpy/tiptap" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TipTap: RTE for Vue</a> - Awesome component giving a fully-featured Rich Text Editor in Vue. - <a href="https://javascriptweekly.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">From</a></p></li></ul>]]></content>
    
